[normal]Written evidence from nfpSynergy [bold][CEP0002][bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction[bold]We wanted to see what the relationship was between a charity’s income and 
[normal]their 
[normal]CEO
[normal]’s
[normal] salary. This was to see if we could establish whether those organisations that paid their CEOs more
[normal], were the largest organisations in either total or voluntary income terms.
[normal] We also wanted to find out whether there was any pattern either in organisationa
[normal]l growth over the last five years or
[normal] in
[normal] CEO pay.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We took around 50 of the UK’s
[normal] best-known charities accordi
[normal]ng to our
[normal] awareness tracking and set
[normal] our
[normal] researchers to work on looking at their accounts
[normal]. Here is what we found.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Some summary facts[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Between 2007
[normal] and 2012:
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The total income of our sample of 50
[normal] charities
[normal] has 
[normal]increased by 17.7%[bold] [bold](or an average increase of 3.5% per year)
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The
[normal]ir
[normal] voluntary income has 
[normal]increased by 11.6%[bold] [bold](or an increase of 2.3% per year)
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Staff costs have 
[normal]increased by 24.2%[bold] [bold](or an average of
[normal] 4.85% per year)
[normal]•
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The salaries of their CEOs have
[normal] 
[normal]increased by 18.0%[bold] [bold](or an average of 3.6% per year)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In terms of changes in CEO pay, those charities that paid their CEOs below £100k in 2007 had increased their CEO salary by an average of 38% (or £32,000 
[normal]in actual money) by 2012. Those who paid their CEOs above £100k in 2007 had increased their CEO salary by 6% (or £9000) by 2012.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The relationship between total income and CEO salary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Chart 1 shows the relationship between CEO pay and total income for our 
[normal]sample of 50 in 2012. The broad relationship is that the higher the total income, the higher the CEO salary, i.e.
[normal] bigger charities pay their CEO
[normal]s more. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A statistical analysis on this relationship 
[normal]shows 
[normal]a high correlation of 0.67 between total income and 
[normal]CEO pay (where the maximum possible correlation is 1, and the minimum is zero when two factors are completely unrelated).
[normal] The correlation in
[normal] 
[normal]CEO pay with total income has 95% confidence limits of 0.47 to 0.80 (so fairly broad confidence intervals). See the
[normal] table 
[normal]below for more detail.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Even just glancing at
[normal] the data reveals that total income appears to be a key variable, but that some charities of a similar size do pay their CEOs very different amounts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The relationship between voluntary[bold] income[bold], staff[bold] costs and CEO salary[bold]As well as total in
[normal]come, we also looked at staff costs
[normal] and voluntary income as other determinants of CEO pay. Th
[normal]e statistical analysis is below:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]R
[normal]Lower limit
[normal]Upper limit
[normal]Total staff costs
[normal]0.68
