[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]So, while total income
[normal] 
[normal]has a correlation of 0.67 o
[normal]f CEO pay, t
[normal]otal staff costs has a correlation of 0.68
[normal] with CEO
[normal] pay and voluntary income 
[normal]a correlation of 0.55
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It should be pointed out that these factors are of course interrelated. The bigger the charity in income terms, the more staff it is likely to have and the more those staff are 
[normal]likely to cost. The reason voluntary income has the lowest correlation with CEO
[normal] pay is that for, some of the charities on the list, it may only be a small portion of total income. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Anyway, for those interested in voluntary income and CEO pay, chart 2 shows the relationship (with one charity removed which distorted the scales)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Ho[bold]w have income and salaries increased over the last 5 years[bold]&#xa0;[bold]If the previous set of data looked at absolute levels of CEO pay, this section looks at how they have changed over the last 5 years (2007 to 2012). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chart 3 shows the percentage increase in CEO p
[normal]ay versus the percentage increase in total income. Unlike chart 1, where the relationship was visible just by looking at the data, the relationship in chart 3 is much less clear. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Overall, the total income of the charities in the sample has grown by 17.7%
[normal] and salaries of the CEOs have grown by 18%. In other words, CEO pay has grown very closely in line with total income.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As the pull-outs show, there are organisations who have grown substantially and whose CEO pay has hardly changed at all, while there are
[normal] organisations wh
[normal]ich have hardly grown at all but
[normal] their CEO pay has increased substantially. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chart 4 looks at the data in a different way and shows how the CEO pay has changed for each organisation in our sample. This reveals something very interesting
[normal]; a £100k salary is a key issue for many boards and when they pay a CEO more than £100k
[normal] for the first time
[normal], they have tended to exceed it by a fair margin in the period 2007-2012.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Speci
[normal]fically, those organisations that
[normal] paid their CEO less than £100k in 20
[normal]07 increased their CEO salary by an average of 38% by 2012 (or a financial increase of £32,000). Those that paid their CEOs more than £100k in 2007 had a much lower increase overall - just 6%
[normal] on average
[normal] (or £9000). Indeed, a number of the charities with th
[normal]e highest paid CEOs in 2007
[normal] had
[normal] 
[normal]reduced[bold] that salary by 2012. So what appears to be happenin
[normal]g is a rebalancing of CEO salaries
[normal] based on market forces. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Many of those who have paid their CEOs under £100k in 2007 decided by 2012 that they needed to pay them more, in some cases substantially so. At the top end of the scale, a number decided that they needed to reduce their CEO pay. We have not done an analys
[normal]is to see what the impact of a change of CEO appears to have on these 
[normal]figures, though we do know that a number of CEO changed in our sample in the period in question
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusion[bold]We draw four conclusions:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Methodology[bold]The sample of the 50
[normal]ish
[normal] charities includes those with the highest levels of spontaneous awareness in our Charity
[normal] Awareness Monitor (CAM). All the UK’s best known charities were therefore in this sample. The reason to take this sample was in order to examine those charities which are in the scrutiny of the public eye, not those who are technically charities but recei
[normal]ve most of their fund
[normal]ing
[normal] from statutory sources or earned income.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We used the formal accounts lodged with the Charity Commission to find out the key data for our research (it is often not possible to find even the most recent accounts on a charity’s websi
[normal]te, let alone the last five years). Using this data, we created a vast spreadsheet of these results. As well as CEO pay, we documented all the numbers of people in the different pay bands. As the actual pay is unknown, we assumed that the actual salary was
[normal] in the middle of a pay band (so if an employee was in the band £120k - £130k we gave them a salary of £125k). We also assumed that the highest paid employee was the CEO. We know of at least one charity where this is not the case. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We decided not to name 
[normal]any individual charity in the analysis in order to focus on the big picture changes, rather than what any one charity has done. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We are happy to share the list of charities in the sample with those who are interested. There is also a more complete set of charts and the complete statistical analysis for those who like that kind of thing.
[normal]&#xa0;
